respectively, about Reid as high commissioner to India, as an important influence on World Bank policy in the early 1960s, and, finally, as founding principal of York University's Glendon College.The authors challenge critics who dismiss Reid as an impractical and ineffectual idealist, demonstrating that his approach to policy-making was sophisticated and his idealism tempered by an astute grasp of the competing interests of a range of national and bureaucratic powers. Reid's reflections on Canada's place in the world remain as relevant and provocative today as when he wrote them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aDonaghy, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aG. Haglund, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranatstein, J.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Alyson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackenzie, Hector, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuirhead, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Geoffrey A.H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoussel, Stéphane, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRoussel, Stéphane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357195240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773571952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773571952/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles